Your task is to write a Jest test case that exposes a specific mutation in a JavaScript/TypeScript project.

MUTATION DETAILS
The mutation affects the following file:
sinks/drain.js
Here is the full content of that file (shown with a <PLACEHOLDER> marker):
'use strict'

module.exports = function drain (op, done) {
  var read, abort

  // Declared here so that it captures the drain's stack trace
  var doneLackingErr
  if (!done) {
    doneLackingErr = new Error('no done callback supplied')
  }

  function sink (_read) {
    read = _read
    if(abort) return sink.abort()
    //this function is much simpler to write if you
    //just use recursion, but by using a while loop
    //we do not blow the stack if the stream happens to be sync.
    ;(function next() {
        var loop = true, cbed = false
        while(loop) {
          cbed = false
          read(null, function (end, data) {
            cbed = true
            if(end = end || abort) {
              loop = false
              if(done) done(end === true ? null : end)
                 <PLACEHOLDER>

                console.warn(doneLackingErr)
                throw end
              }
            }
            else if(op && false === op(data) || abort) {
              loop = false
              read(abort || true, done || function () {})
            }
            else if(!loop){
              next()
            }
          })
          if(!cbed) {
            loop = false
            return
          }
        }
      })()
  }

  sink.abort = function (err, cb) {
    if('function' == typeof err)
      cb = err, err = true
    abort = err || true
    if(read) return read(abort, cb || function () {})
  }

  return sink
}

In the original code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

-                 else if(end && end !== true) {
In the mutated code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

+                 else if(end && true) {


YOUR TASK
Write one Jest test file that:
    1. Passes when run against the original code.
    2. Fails when run against the mutated code.
    3. Tests the behavior of the mutated file in a way that reliably detects the mutation.
The test will be saved at the following path, relative to this test-generation project’s root:
llm-cache/anthropic_claude-sonnet-4.6/temp_0.5/withoutTests/cached/artifacts/pull-stream/attempt_1/pending_category/mutant-980c0a3/testCase.test.ts

ALLOWED LIBRARIES
You may use:
    1. Any built-in Node.js modules (e.g., fs, path, crypto, etc.).

You may not use any other third-party libraries.

Looking at the mutation, the change is:
- Original: `else if(end && end !== true)` - only warns/throws when `end` is a non-true error
- Mutated: `else if(end && true)` - always warns/throws even when `end === true` (normal stream end)

The original code: when a stream ends normally (`end === true`), it calls `done(null)` and does NOT throw. When there's an actual error, it calls `done(error)` AND warns/throws.

The mutated code: when a stream ends normally (`end === true`), it would also try to warn and throw, even though `done` was already called with `null`.

To detect this mutation, I need to create a scenario where:
1. No `done` callback is provided
2. The stream ends normally (with `end === true`)
3. In the original: nothing bad happens (the `else if` is false since `end === true` and `end !== true` is false)
4. In the mutated code: it would try to `throw end` (throw `true`)

```typescript
import drain from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/sinks/drain.js";

describe("drain sink", () => {
  it("should not throw when stream ends normally without a done callback", () => {
    // Create a simple source that emits one item then ends
    const values = [1];
    let callCount = 0;

    function source(end: any, cb: (end: any, data?: any) => void) {
      if (end) {
        cb(end, null);
        return;
      }
      if (callCount < values.length) {
        cb(null, values[callCount++]);
      } else {
        // Normal end of stream
        cb(true, null);
      }
    }

    // No done callback provided - this is key to triggering the mutation
    // In original: when end === true, the else if(end && end !== true) is false, so no throw
    // In mutated: when end === true, the else if(end && true) is true, so it throws true
    expect(() => {
      const sink = drain(null);
      sink(source);
    }).not.toThrow();
  });
});
```

Wait, let me re-read the code. The `doneLackingErr` is set when `!done`. The `else if` block runs `console.warn(doneLackingErr)` and `throw end`. So if `done` is not provided and stream ends with `true`, the mutation would cause a throw.

But if `done` IS provided, the `if(done) done(...)` branch runs and then the `else if` wouldn't run anyway... actually looking more carefully, there's no `else` before the `else if` - the `else if` is an `else if` to the `if(done)` block. So if `done` is provided, the `else if` won't execute.

The test case above should work. Let me finalize it:

```typescript
import drain from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/sinks/drain.js";

describe("drain sink", () => {
  it("should not throw when stream ends normally without a done callback", () => {
    const values = [1, 2, 3];
    let callCount = 0;

    function source(end: any, cb: (end: any, data?: any) => void) {
      if (end) {
        cb(end, null);
        return;
      }
      if (callCount < values.length) {
        cb(null, values[callCount++]);
      } else {
        cb(true, null);
      }
    }

    // No done callback - original code won't throw on normal end (end === true)
    // Mutated code will throw because else if(end && true) is true when end === true
    expect(() => {
      const sink = drain(null);
      sink(source);
    }).not.toThrow();
  });
});
```
